On Wednesday, May 18, the Czech government approved a change in the terms of payment of humanitarian aid to Ukrainian refugees.
Today, all arriving Ukrainian refugees are entitled to a first aid payment of 5000 CZK, without any additional conditions (only a temporary protection visa is required).
In order to receive the same amount for the next five months, the applicant must prove his difficult financial situation ‚Äì to be considered unemployed, not to have property in the Czech Republic, etc.
The Ministry of Labor decided to change this practice as follows:
1Ô∏è‚É£ The first payment of benefits will cease to be unconditional.
If a refugee is provided with free housing, daily multiple meals and hygiene supplies, then he will not be able to claim the payment of 5000 crowns.
The authorities will begin to believe that basic assistance was provided in kind (housing, food and hygiene products), which means that the purpose of humanitarian aid has been fulfilled and there is no need to pay money.
This measure is designed to solve the problem of Roma refugees from Ukraine.
Many of them come to the Czech Republic only for financial assistance.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Only those refugees who prove immediate need (lack of work, etc.) will still be entitled to the payment of second, third, fourth, fifth and sixth benefits.
However, two more conditions will be added:
üìå As in the first paragraph, only those Ukrainians who have not been provided with free housing, daily multiple meals and hygiene supplies will be able to receive cash assistance;
üìå the applicant must actually reside in the Czech Republic.
This is necessary to stop the practice of "tourism for help", when a refugee lives in one country, and comes to the Czech Republic for several days exclusively for money.
According to the law, every foreigner is obliged to inform the Ministry of Internal Affairs about the change of residence within three working days after moving.
If the address in the application form for the payment of benefits does not match the address indicated in the database of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, the applicant will be asked to provide evidence that she really lives in the Czech Republic.
Otherwise, the payment of assistance will be denied.
At the moment, the Czech Republic has spent UAH 2.626 billion on the payment of humanitarian aid. CZK.
