From Nikopol to Prague
Maryna is from Nikopol, Dnipropetrovsk region.
It was there that she met her husband and gave birth to two children - a son and a daughter.
She worked as an architect at the State Nikopol Institution.
"I am an architect of buildings and structures by education, I graduated from the Dnipropetrovsk Academy of Architecture with honors.
Before that, I studied at an art school, graduated from the lyceum with a degree in design," Maryna said.
And everything was fine, but on February 24, her life changed.
Like millions of Ukrainians fleeing the onslaught of Russian aggression in Ukraine, Maryna, without hesitation, left Ukraine with her children.
Prague became a shelter for the woman.
"Of course, a new city, big, crowded... A new language, but Czech is very similar to Ukrainian, so I understand a lot of what Czechs tell me.
Knowledge of English and sign language also came in handy.
In addition, I am not ashamed to ask for help from the Czechs and have never felt any aggression from them.
I thank them for this," Maryna shared.
According to her, in solving issues related to finding housing, obtaining a visa and insurance, applying for benefits, she was helped by people who have been living in Prague for a long time.
But she has to solve many problems on her own.
